<subSubSection id="388573266AE9D351923EF5A9474049F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="B2B84F2FD0D815A4864FD08510251D37" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AC1EEEE1073C8956B100DFC769CEE3F9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very distinctive species with woody stems and a subcylindrical hypocrateriform corolla which is enclosed by a pair of showy bracteoles. As in 
<taxonomicName id="EA75BE08E8461A268E5DA196DD8D8DDE" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumosa">
<emphasis id="A90EB42B5FBBE8A8D16992242AB7C2E4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea dumosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the petiole and peduncle are partially fused. Although very distinct 
<taxonomicName id="676D34D0CE9D184D8B6DE9F9BCEA1AA4" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bracteata">
<emphasis id="B6756C3EB2C5B53827F8670E9E829F55" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. bracteata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also very variable. The leaves are usually glabrous but a pubescent form (
<taxonomicName id="FA075C81742DDFA408289798DD59871A" authority="" authorityName="" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Exogonium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="bracteatum" variety="pubescens">
var. 
<emphasis id="4844BBA180E877DEEC5B6D522F54782B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) occasionally occurs; the bracteoles and corolla are usually pink but plants with greenish bracteoles (
<taxonomicName id="B714B5AF0C5B45AA4D6746180560659F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="bracteata" variety="viridibracta">
var. 
<emphasis id="B4D85E9EB5AA98E31906D81BE487C6A9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">viridibracta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and green corollas are occasionally found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9A5539A7BBDC5A0A7DD07E182C4F55EF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="B9827EC063B82D4249BB562B64444998" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bracteata">
<emphasis id="6E19479FD8A37814F27A0CCBBF297FEA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea bracteata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
flowers in the dry season, fide 
<normalizedToken id="434482D12EFFE4E1F0FB3682E956EB09" originalValue="Chemás-Jaramillo">Chemas-Jaramillo</normalizedToken>
and Bullock (2005).
</paragraph>
